### Step 5: `extensions/pulseboard/src/types.ts`

Account config types and resolved account. Mirrors Nostr's `types.ts` pattern but adds board and
username concepts.

Key contents:
- `PulseBoardBoardConfig` — per-board settings (`requireMention`, `allowFrom`, `tools`, `systemPrompt`)
- `PulseBoardAccountConfig` — top-level config shape (mirrors `NostrAccountConfig` + `IrcAccountConfig` for groups)
  - `token?: SecretInput` — API token (required for "configured")
  - `serverUrl?: string` — WebSocket server URL (e.g. `wss://pb.example.com`)
  - `username?: string` — bot username on PulseBoard
  - `dmPolicy?`, `allowFrom?` — standard DM security
  - `groupPolicy?` — "open" | "allowlist" | "blocked"
  - `groupAllowFrom?` — board-level sender allowlist
  - `boards?: Record<string, PulseBoardBoardConfig>` — per-board overrides
  - `markdown?`, `enabled?`, `name?`
- `ResolvedPulseBoardAccount` — resolved runtime account
  - `accountId`, `name?`, `enabled`, `configured` (requires token)
  - `token`, `serverUrl`, `username`
  - `config: PulseBoardAccountConfig`
- `PulseBoardInboundMessage` — inbound message structure
  - `messageId: string`
  - `senderId: string` — sender username
  - `boardName?: string` — set for board messages; absent for DMs
  - `text: string`
  - `timestamp: number`
  - `isGroup: boolean`
- Helper functions: `resolveDefaultPulseBoardAccountId`, `listPulseBoardAccountIds`,
  `resolvePulseBoardAccount` — follow the Nostr pattern using
  `openclaw/plugin-sdk/account-id` and `openclaw/plugin-sdk/account-resolution`
- `CoreConfig` — `OpenClawConfig & { channels?: { pulseboard?: PulseBoardAccountConfig } }`

